Business investment in capital goods should be stronger, consumer spending firmer and government activity less of a drag, said High Frequency Economics analyst Ian Shepherdson.

Other data show the economy ended 2011 on a strong note. Firms invested more in equipment and machinery in December. People are buying more cars and consumer confidence is rising.

Unemployment fell to 8.5 per cent last month - the lowest level in nearly three years - after the sixth straight month of solid hiring. Even the depressed housing market has shown some improvement.

But many economists fear that a recession in Europe could dampen demand for U.S. manufactured goods and slow growth. Without more jobs and better pay, consumer spending is likely to stagnate.

