That was a year and a half later than it had said earlier. The central bank also reduced its outlook for growth this year, from as much as 2.9 per cent forecast in November down to 2.7 per cent.

The Fed also sees unemployment falling as low as 8.2 per cent this year. U.S. stocks fell after the Commerce Department data came out, with the Dow Jones dropping 0.29 per cent this morning.

‘The Fed is attempting to shield the economy from a potentially more severe recession in Europe,’ said Ryan Sweet, a senior economist at Moody's Analytics in West Chester, Pennsylvania.

‘Even though the economy improved last quarter there are a number of headwinds and a lot of uncertainty surrounding Europe, emerging markets and also U.S. fiscal policy.’

